The key insight in this solution is recognizing that $\sqrt{27} = \sqrt{3^3} = 3\sqrt{3}$. This allows us to simplify the denominator by combining like terms, which in this case are $3\sqrt{3}$ and $7\sqrt{27} = 21\sqrt{3}$.
Step 1: Simplify $7\sqrt{27}$
$$\begin{align*}
7\sqrt{27} &= 7 \cdot 3\sqrt{3} \\
&= 21\sqrt{3}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Rewrite the expression with the simplified term
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{8}{3\sqrt{3}+21\sqrt{3}}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Combine like terms in the denominator
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{8}{3\sqrt{3}+21\sqrt{3}} &= \frac{8}{24\sqrt{3}}
\end{align*}$$

Step 4: Simplify the fraction
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{8}{24\sqrt{3}} &= \frac{1}{3\sqrt{3}}
\end{align*}$$

Step 5: Rationalize the denominator by multiplying both the numerator and denominator by $\sqrt{3}$
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{3\sqrt{3}} &= \frac{1 \cdot \sqrt{3}}{3\sqrt{3} \cdot \sqrt{3}} \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{3}}{9}
\end{align*}$$
The simplified and rationalized expression is $\boxed{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{9}}$.

The approach taken in this solution is straightforward and follows the definition of a function. By substituting the given value (7) for the input variable (x) in the function, we can directly calculate the output value of the function at that specific point. This is a fundamental concept in mathematics and is used to evaluate functions at various points in their domains.
Let's solve this problem step by step:

Step 1: Substitute $x$ with $7$ in the given function.
$$\begin{align*}
f(7) & = \dfrac{5(7)+1}{7-1}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Simplify the numerator by multiplying 5 and 7, then adding 1.
$$\begin{align*}
f(7) & = \dfrac{35+1}{7-1}
\\ & = \dfrac{36}{7-1}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Simplify the denominator by subtracting 1 from 7.
$$\begin{align*}
f(7) & = \dfrac{36}{6}
\end{align*}$$

Step 4: Simplify the fraction by dividing both the numerator and denominator by their greatest common factor (6).
$$\begin{align*}
f(7) & = \dfrac{36 \div 6}{6 \div 6}
\\ & = \dfrac{6}{1}
\\ & = 6
\end{align*}$$

Therefore, the value of $f(7)$ is $6$.
The value of $f(7)$ is $\boxed{6}$.

The provided solution uses long division in base 4, similar to the process used in base 10. It demonstrates that the same division algorithm can be applied in different bases, as long as the multiplication and subtraction operations are performed in the corresponding base.
1. Set up the long division in base 4:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && && \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && && \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && && \\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

2. Divide $11_4$ into the leftmost digit of $1023_4$. $11_4$ goes into $1_4$ zero times, so write a 0 above the line in the quotient.

3. Multiply $11_4$ by $0_4$ and write the result $0_4$ below $1_4$. Subtract and bring down the next digit $0_4$:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 0 & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&0& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 1&0&2 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & \\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

4. Divide $11_4$ into $102_4$. $11_4$ goes into $102_4$ three times, so write a 3 above the line in the quotient. Multiply $11_4$ by $3_4$ ($33_4$) and write the result below $102_4$:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&0& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 1&0&2 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 3&3 \\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & \\
   \end{array}
   $$

5. Subtract $33_4$ from $102_4$ and bring down the next digit $3_4$:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&0& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 1&0&2 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 3&3 \\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 0&3 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

6. Divide $11_4$ into $3_4$. $11_4$ goes into $3_4$ zero times, so write a 3 above the line in the quotient. Multiply $11_4$ by $3_4$ ($33_4$) and write the result below $3_4$:
   $$
   \begin{array}{cc|cccc}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & 3 & 3 \\
   \cline{3-6}
   1 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 2 & 3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 0&0& \downarrow \\ \cline{4-5}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && 1&0&2 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 3&3 \\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & 0&3 \\
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & 3 3\\ \cline{5-6}
   \multicolumn{2}{r}{} && & & 0 \\
   \end{array}
   $$

7. Subtract $33_4$ from $3_4$, resulting in $0_4$. The division is complete.
The quotient of $1023_4 \div 11_4$ in base 4 is $\boxed{33_4}$.
